web_tavily.title: Mutation Testing: The Tests to Test your Tests
web_tavily.content:
```
{ "$schema": "./node_modules/@stryker-mutator/core/schema/stryker-schema.json", "packageManager": "npm", "reporters": ["html", "clear-text", "progress"], "testRunner": "jest", "coverageAnalysis": "perTest", "mutate": [ "src//.js", "!src//.test.js", "!src//.spec.js" ]}
```

Let me break down what’s happening here:

 `packageManager`: Tells Stryker how to install dependencies in the sandbox
 `reporters`: Defines how you want to see the results (HTML report is fantastic for detailed analysis)
 `testRunner`: Which test runner you're using
 `coverageAnalysis`: "perTest" is usually the sweet spot for performance vs accuracy
 `mutate`: Which files to mutate (notice we're excluding test files – we don't want to mutate our tests!)

### Step 3: Running Your First Mutation Test [...] ### Step 1: Installation

First things first, let’s get Stryker installed. I recommend installing it as a dev dependency:

```
npm install --save-dev @stryker-mutator/core
```

If you’re using Jest (and who isn’t these days?):

```
npm install --save-dev @stryker-mutator/jest-runner
```

For TypeScript projects, add:

```
npm install --save-dev @stryker-mutator/typescript-checker
```

### Step 2: Configuration

Stryker uses a configuration file to understand your project structure. Create a `stryker.conf.json` file in your project root: [...] The benefits are pretty compelling:

 Quality over quantity: You’ll write fewer, better tests instead of just chasing coverage numbers
 Bug prevention: Catches logical errors that might slip past traditional testing
 Test improvement: Identifies weak spots in your test suite that need attention
 Confidence boost: Gives you genuine confidence that your tests are doing their job

## Getting Started with Stryker: Your Mutation Testing Companion

Stryker is hands-down the most popular mutation testing framework for JavaScript and TypeScript projects, and for good reason it’s powerful, well-maintained, and surprisingly easy to set up. Let me walk you through getting it running on your project.

> Note: Stryker is also available for .NET projects as Stryker.NET

# Installation

## Introduction​

Playwright Test is an end-to-end test framework for modern web apps. It bundles test runner, assertions, isolation, parallelization and rich tooling. Playwright supports Chromium, WebKit and Firefox on Windows, Linux and macOS, locally or in CI, headless or headed, with native mobile emulation for Chrome (Android) and Mobile Safari.

You will learn

 How to install Playwright
 What's installed
 How to run the example test
 How to open the HTML test report

## Installing Playwright​

Get started by installing Playwright using one of the following methods.

### Using npm, yarn or pnpm​

The command below either initializes a new project or adds Playwright to an existing one.

 npm
 yarn
 pnpm [...] ```
pnpm exec playwright test --ui pnpm  exec  playwright test  --ui
```

See the detailed guide on UI Mode for watch filters, step details and trace integration.

## Updating Playwright​

Update Playwright and download new browser binaries and their dependencies:

 npm
 yarn
 pnpm

```
npm install -D @playwright/test@latest npm  install  -D @playwright/test@latestnpx playwright install --with-deps npx playwright install --with-deps
```

```
yarn add --dev @playwright/test@latest yarn  add  --dev @playwright/test@latestyarn playwright install --with-deps yarn  playwright install --with-deps
```

```
pnpm install --save-dev @playwright/test@latest pnpm  install --save-dev @playwright/test@latestpnpm exec playwright install --with-deps pnpm  exec  playwright install --with-deps
``` [...] Check your installed version:

 npm
 yarn
 pnpm

```
npx playwright --version npx playwright --version
```

```
yarn playwright --version yarn  playwright --version
```

```
pnpm exec playwright --version pnpm  exec  playwright --version
```

## System requirements​

 Node.js: latest 20.x, 22.x or 24.x.
 Windows 11+, Windows Server 2019+ or Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL).
 macOS 14 (Ventura) or later.
 Debian 12 / 13, Ubuntu 22.04 / 24.04 (x86-64 or arm64).

## What's next​

 Write tests using web-first assertions, fixtures and locators
 Run single or multiple tests; headed mode
 Generate tests with Codegen
 View a trace of your tests

# Stryker Mutator

Test your tests with mutation testing.

Strykerman

## Getting started with Stryker

## Features

### Mutations

Control more than 30 supported mutations.

### Speed

Use code analysis and parallel test runner processes to speed things up.

### Test runner agnostic

Run tests with your favorite test runner.

### Open source

Free as in Speech. Maintained by the open source community at GitHub.

### Multilingual

Stryker has support for JavaScript & TypeScript, C# and Scala.

### Clever reports

Use clever reports to sniff out surviving mutants and improve test effectiveness.
